libpng row padding-bit non-determinism
======================================

Background
----------

Debian bug #1118385 / tex-k discussion (May 2026) reported that pdfTeX
produces different PDF output on consecutive runs when including a
particular PNG image (valuators.png from the fltk1.4 documentation,
567 x 506, 4-bit colormap, non-interlaced) even with
SOURCE_DATE_EPOCH/FORCE_SOURCE_DATE set.

Root cause
----------

For a sub-byte pixel depth (here 4 bpp) and a width that is not a
multiple of 8/bpp (567 * 4 = 2268 bits = 283.5 bytes), the last byte of
each decoded scanline holds the last pixel in its high nibble and 4
padding bits in its low nibble.

In libpng-1.6.58, pngrutil.c:png_combine_row() (non-interlaced path)
deliberately preserves the destination buffer's existing bits in that
padding region:

    end_byte = *end_ptr;                            /* dest bits BEFORE memcpy */
    memcpy(dp, sp, PNG_ROWBYTES(...));              /* whole row from sp       */
    *end_ptr = (end_byte & end_mask)                /* restore dest pad bits   */
             | (*end_ptr & ~end_mask);

pdfTeX allocates its row buffer with xtalloc -> xmalloc (uninitialized
memory). The padding bits in the output PDF therefore reflect whatever
was on the heap at allocation time, so successive runs produce
different bytes for those bits and the PDFs differ.

The PNG spec requires encoders to set these padding bits to zero;
readers should not import uninitialized caller memory into the decoded
row.

Fix
---

In libs/libpng/libpng-src/pngrutil.c, png_combine_row() now clears the
padding bits instead of restoring them from the destination buffer:

    if (end_ptr != NULL)
       *end_ptr = (png_byte)(*end_ptr & ~end_mask);

Test program
------------

The file ./pngtest.c (kept outside the libpng tree on purpose; it
links against libpng and is not part of libpng itself) decodes a PNG
three times, pre-filling the user-provided row buffer with 0x00, 0xff,
and 0xaa before each png_read_row(). It prints the last 4 bytes of
the first decoded row for each fill.

  /* see pngtest.c */

The trigger image is available in ./valuators.png, and can be obtained via

    curl -sL "https://salsa.debian.org/fltk-team/fltk1.4/-/raw/main/documentation/src/valuators.png" \
        -o ./valuators.png

Demonstrate the bug against the system (unpatched) libpng:

    gcc pngtest.c -lpng -o pngtest
    ./pngtest valuators.png

Expected (buggy) output -- the low nibble of the last byte mirrors the
fill, proving the destination buffer's bits leak into the decoded row:

    fill=0x00 row0 last bytes: 00 00 00 00
    fill=0xff row0 last bytes: 00 00 00 0f
    fill=0xaa row0 last bytes: 00 00 00 0a

Demonstrate the fix against the patched in-tree libpng (after building
under Build/source/Work):

    gcc pngtest.c \
        -I.../Build/source/libs/libpng/libpng-src \
        -I.../Build/source/Work/libs/libpng \
        .../Build/source/Work/libs/libpng/libpng.a \
        -lz -lm -o pngtest_patched
    ./pngtest_patched valuators.png

Expected (fixed) output -- padding bits are zero regardless of the
caller's buffer contents:

    fill=0x00 row0 last bytes: 00 00 00 00
    fill=0xff row0 last bytes: 00 00 00 00
    fill=0xaa row0 last bytes: 00 00 00 00

Notes
-----

- A pdfTeX-side workaround (memset(row, 0, rowbytes) before each
  png_read_row) would also eliminate the symptom, but the same trap
  exists for every other libpng caller. Fixing libpng once is the
  right layer.
- The fix only changes the non-interlaced memcpy tail in
  png_combine_row(); the interlaced display/sparkle paths are
  untouched.
